So too the merces, like the pretium, must be certa and vera, but need not be iusta, understanding these terms in the senses already given to them under Tit. ²33 nor, finally, need the letter be dominus os that which he lets (Dig. 19. 2. 7 ; ib. 9pr. and 6); else subletting would have been impossible.

Transactions ol three different kinds are included under this contract: (1) Locatio conductio rerum, the letting by one (locator) and hiring by another (conductor) os a thing moveable or immoveable (eg. a house with its premiseS, in which case the hirer was called inquilinus: or agricultural land, when he was called colonus, Bk ii. 1. 36 supr), or even ol a res incorporalis, e.g. a usufruct, Dig. 7. 1. 12. 2; ib. 38.

(2) Locatio conductio operarum, the letting by one (locator) ot' his services only to another (conductor), as in all contracts ol free service.

(3) Locatio conductio operis, where one (conductor) engages to execute a specific piece oi work, e. g. build a house, a ship, a carriage, etc, for another (locator). Here the ordinary use ol the ternis describing the parties is inverted, the one who contracts to do the wo'rk, and who we should say is hired, being regarded as the hirer.
